  "prompt": "How are particles arranged in solids, liquids and gases?",
  "response": "In solids, liquids, and gases, particles are arranged differently, reflecting their distinct physical properties:\n\n1. **Solids:**\n   - Particles are closely packed together in a fixed, orderly arrangement.\n   - They have definite shapes and volumes due to the rigid structure.\n   - Particles vibrate around fixed positions but do not move freely.\n\n2. **Liquids:**\n   - Particles are closely packed, but not in a fixed arrangement.\n   - They have a definite volume but not a definite shape, conforming to the shape of their container.\n   - Particles can move and slide past each other, allowing liquids to flow.\n\n3. **Gases:**\n   - Particles are widely spaced apart and not arranged in any particular order.\n   - They have neither a definite shape nor a definite volume, expanding to fill the container.\n   - Particles move rapidly and freely in all directions, experiencing frequent collisions.\n\nThese differing arrangements result in the distinct physical properties observed among solids, liquids, and gases.",
